<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-10-14T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-10-14T15:00:00-05:00" n="459" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d459">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">711.94/845: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in Japan (<persName type="to">Grew</persName>)</hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-10-14T15:00:00-05:00">October 14, 1933—3
                                p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>96. Department’s 89, October 6, 5 p.m.,<note n="60" xml:id="d459fn60"><ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_125"><hi rend="italic">Foreign
                                        Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 125</ref>.</note> [paragraph] 1. An officer of
                            the Department has spoken with the Japanese Ambassador on the subject of
                            the mooted good will mission, in discouragement thereof. The Ambassador
                            states that he has not been informed or interrogated <pb facs="0536" n="434" xml:id="pg_434"/> by his Foreign Office with regard to this
                            project, but that he shares the view that such mission would serve no
                            useful purpose and if interrogated would advise to that effect.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>